  "doc_id": "26159",
  "text": "The method proposed in this paper could be used by other research groups using RFID to study social insects to better analyze the RFID data and overcome the issue of missed readings which are commonly experienced with electronic tagging. This has an important and positive implications for those using RFID data in insect behavior modelling. Study in the design of environmental sensor networks which involves animal-borne instruments as mobile sensor nodes [CITATION_1] could also benefit from this work. He has a considerable amount of experience operating in research laboratories, field-based research studies, bee husbandry, management, and processes within the commercial apiculture setting. His veterinary training provides him a unique perspective moving into this field, with a focus on the holistic management of disease, from recognition of risk factors and prevention of disease, through principles of diagnosis and treatment. He has a view to applying the veterinary training to challenges afflicting the apiculture industry, both locally and globally. His primary career focuses are in the field of honey bee health and disease research.",
